            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/003B/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>003B</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/lectures/003B/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Boolean valuations: implication">Boolean valuations: implication</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>     This is the weird one.
    I won't make excuses; Boolean implication is not a very good approximation of "if...then".
    Don't lean too hard, then, on the understanding you already have of "if...then"; just roll with it.
    Here's the table:
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>21</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/003M/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>003M</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/003M/</fr:route>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:table style="border-collapse: collapse;">
  <html:thead><html:tr>
    <html:td class="topedge leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\rightarrow ]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    <html:td class="topedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  </html:tr></html:thead>
  <html:tbody>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
    <html:tr>
      <html:td class="leftedge"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
      <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex></html:td>
    </html:tr>
  </html:tbody>
</html:table>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>    That is, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p \rightarrow  q)]]></fr:tex> comes out to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> in all cases except the one case where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.
    It's relatively uncontroversial that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  q]]></fr:tex> should be false when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> is true and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex> is false; if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> really did imply <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> is true, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex> should be true as well, or at least so goes a pretty plausible line of reasoning.
    So the upper-right corner of the table is pretty strongly supported.
    But all of the other three entries can be (and have been) contested.
</html:p>
            <html:p>     Note that, given the above table, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p \rightarrow  q) = v(\neg  p \lor  q)]]></fr:tex> for every Boolean valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>, no matter what <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(q)]]></fr:tex> are.
    (Later this week, we'll pick up a word for that: <html:em>equivalence</html:em>.)
    This might be the best way to see what's behind the table above: if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>, then we might think that either <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> isn't the case or else it is, and if it is, then since it implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex> we can conclude that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex> would be as well.
    So if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  q]]></fr:tex> is true, this might lead us to think that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  p \lor  q]]></fr:tex> should also be true.
    Conversely, suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  p \lor  q]]></fr:tex> is true.
    Then what could we conclude if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> were to be true?
    Well, since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  p]]></fr:tex> can't both be true, it would imply that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex> must be the true component of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  p \lor  q]]></fr:tex>.
    That is, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> would imply <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>.
    There's a lot you could quarrel with in these lines of reasoning, but I think something like them is probably the best motivation for this table for implication.
    Regardless, this is how Boolean implication works, and we'll work with it in this form.</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>21</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/003C/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>003C</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/003C/</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Side note</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>There was, alas, an embarrassing moment, mainly from the 1950s to the 1990s or so, where a decent number of philosophers genuinely defended the idea that the Boolean implication is not just an approximation, but actually fully gives the truth conditions for English "if...then" statements.
    To see that this doesn't work, here's an old facetious proof of the existence of God:</html:p>
                <html:p>It's false to say that if there's a God, then the prayers of the wicked will be answered.
    So, by the Boolean truth table, the antecedent of that "if...then" must be true; so there is a God.</html:p>
                <html:p>Even theists should (and do) reject this line of reasoning; it's pretty obviously bad reasoning.
    Embarrassments like this for the idea that English conditionals are Boolean implications can be multiplied more or less endlessly; the view is as refuted as anything ever gets.
    But if you happen across certain philosophy from around that time period, you should be aware that many authors did in fact believe this, despite the obvious problems.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
If you're interested in learning more about this, I recommend the book <fr:link href="/lectures/003D/" title="https://negation.rocks/lectures/003D/" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/003D/" display-uri="003D" type="local">Relevant Logics and their Rivals, vol. 1</fr:link>.
Note that this was written during the period in question!
It's good fun, and it gives a particularly vitriolic (and particularly Australian) takedown of what was at the time practically an accepted orthodoxy. 
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
